I've been to a lot of Spanish restaurants and I definitely have to give DOS31 Cocina Bar 5 stars.  If I could give it 10 stars, I would!  My experiences there have been nothing but positive.  The owners are super nice and try to make you feel like you're part of their family.  I enjoy the quality of food - definitely 5-star quality - and the timely service is excellent.  Make sure you go there with a big appetite and be ready to go home with a doggy bag because the portions of food are enormous and their prices are the best around. They also have bottomless drink brunch specials - the dishes are delicious and the drinks are even better.  The best Passion Fruit Mimosas ever!! They also have different events including karaoke Sundays which is always fun for everyone involved, especially the brave customers who take on the challenge.  DOS31, thank you for your SERVICE and keep up the GREAT WORK!!  -  ********** 10 stars from me to you!

Super nice and hospitable people who own and work at this longtime local staple for Latino cuisine, making us feel at home. For many years under the old owners, it was a Puerto Rican menu and now in the last few years the restaurant  is under Dominican management, yet except for a few minor differences and subtlety of flavor, it really doesn't matter because you'll find that the standard comfort foods associated with both cultures, are still available...things like stewed chicken,  rice and beans, roast pork, etc.. I would have given 4 stars but some of the food we had could've been better. I had mofongo with fried pork that lacked a little flavor and was a little overfilled with meat. The roast pork (pernil) was dry...perhaps because it was already close to 8pm and had been roasted hours earlier, but that shouldn't matter. Still need to have quality the whole dinnertime through. Music was a little loud for my taste but it's not unusual to encounter this at restaurants that feature Dominican or Puerto Rican food. I'll have a side of bachata with my tostones! When I'm in the neighborhood, we'll be back for our comfort food and try other things. Would love to see this place grow and thrive in a neighborhood that is underrepresented in latino food but they need to take it up a notch or two and make the food rock like I know that it can!

It seems like this place is a fun nightclub in the evenings, with DJs posted on the signs and a top shelf bar. Truthfully, I almost didn't post this because I don't want the secret to get out, but then again I want to support the people who lived in Williamsburg before the gentrification. I had the rice and beans and plantains with chicken - 9 bucks and change! Come support and tip your service people well!
